@node INSTALLATION "Installation"

 Copy SubStr to C:

 Copy this Guide to whereever you want.

@endnode

@node USAGE "Usage"

 Call from the shell as following:

  @{i}STR=STRING/A,POS=POSITION,LEN=LENGTH/@{ui}

 All arguments are optional.

  STR=STRING/A  is the string you want to get a part of. If it title includes
                spaces you need to enclose it with "".

  POS=POSITION  is the position the substring begins at. You can use decimal
                (e.g. 12), hexadecimal (e.g. $C) or binary (e.g. %1100) encoding.
                Argument is optional. Defaults to 1.
                Value provided must be 1 or greater. Else the default value is used.

  LEN=LENGTH/A  The length of the substring. As with position you may use decimal,
                hex or binary values.

  ?             Shows above template and asks you for input. If you provide a ?
                again, you will get a long description text (like this one).



 Important: It's up to you to ensure that the last position of the substring
            doesn't exceed the length of the string !

 Exmaples:

 @{i}substr "Hello world !" POS -%101001 LEN=5@{ui}

 @{i}substr STRING "Hello world !" POSITION=0 5@{ui}

 @{i}substr "Hello world !" LEN=$5 POS=1@{ui}

 @{i}substr STR "Hello world !" LENGTH=5@{ui}

 Will all output @{i}Hello@{ui}.

 @{i}substr "Hello world !" POS 7 5@{ui}

 Will output @{i}world@{ui}.

 @{i}substr Hello 3 4@{ui}

 Will not output anything but result in an error code of 20 !
 If you try and read four characters beginning at position 3 means to read
 all characters from position 3 to 6. But the string provided has only a length
 of 5 characters.

@endnode

